               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280529-247-person1337">
                  HENRY 
                  GLOVER
               <interp inst="t18280529-247-person1337" type="surname" value="GLOVER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-247-person1337" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280529-247-person1337" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner has been <rs id="t18280529-247-deflabel1359" type="occupation">shopman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-247-defend1335 t18280529-247-deflabel1359"></join> to Mr. Thomas Dobson, and others, <rs id="t18280529-247-viclabel1360" type="occupation">jewellers</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-247-victim1336 t18280529-247-viclabel1360"></join>, of <placeName id="t18280529-247-crimeloc1361">Leadenhall-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280529-247-crimeloc1361" type="placeName" value="Leadenhall-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280529-247-crimeloc1361" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280529-247-off1357 t18280529-247-crimeloc1361"></join>, for about seven weeks. On the 11th of April, as I went to a back door, I picked up a small coral necklace; I made strict inquiry about it of the prisoner and every person in the house, but could get no information; in about an hour the prisoner came to me, and said, "Mr. Glover, I am sorry anybody should be blamed for my errors, as it respects that coral necklace; I dropped it myself:" he said he had a commission from his mother to get a necklace of that description for his sister and he had taken it to show her, and on Monday he should return it, or pay the money; I said it was a thing he had no right to do, and sent for Mr. Dobson into the warehouse; I then said Styles had said he had dropped the necklace, and that he wished to show it to his mother; I should have said he was about to leave us; we thought it prudent to have him searched, and sent for an officer: when the officer came, he put his hand into his pocket, and pulled out a variety of articles of his employer's property: he delivered up the key of his trunk, in which were found other articles mentioned in another indictment; a duplicate of the gold neck-chain was found in a pocket-book, on his person - he said it was our property.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BARRY. Q. All he said was, that it was your's? A. Yes, I am one of the partners.</p>
               <p>
            
